So let's look at them.

23
00:01:53,920 --> 00:02:01,116
First, we recommend to perform
an LCA with a screening approach.

24
00:02:01,116 --> 00:02:03,067
So carry it in two steps.

25
00:02:03,067 --> 00:02:09,213
A first screening phase, okay, which will
take about half of the total time and

26
00:02:09,213 --> 00:02:14,091
where you cover the entire LCA but
look at orders of magnitude.

27
00:02:14,091 --> 00:02:18,147
And then you choose what
needs to be improved,

28
00:02:18,147 --> 00:02:24,387
refined because it's important or
brings substantial uncertainty,

29
00:02:24,387 --> 00:02:30,843
and you perform a detailed analysis
of these points which are important.

30
00:02:30,843 --> 00:02:35,072
And that's valid for
many scientific approach.

31
00:02:35,072 --> 00:02:39,172
Second, for the goal definition,
remember the popcorn,

32
00:02:39,172 --> 00:02:44,349
how the functional unit was crucial and
could completely change results.

33
00:02:44,349 --> 00:02:50,715
So be sure and check that the functional
unit is really representing the main

34
00:02:50,715 --> 00:02:57,186
function and the service of the product
and is a good representation of that.

35
00:02:57,186 --> 00:03:03,073
Should be metric which increases
if the functional unit doubles.

36
00:03:03,073 --> 00:03:07,087
For example,
the emission should also double.

37
00:03:07,087 --> 00:03:13,688
So it's an extensive metric which
is not a ratio, so it's not.

38
00:03:13,688 --> 00:03:19,778
Units are not something per
something in that case.

39
00:03:19,778 --> 00:03:26,411
System boundaries, third critical point
of the goal and system definition.

40
00:03:26,411 --> 00:03:29,929
It should cover the same
functional reality.

41
00:03:29,929 --> 00:03:36,742
Remember the fast food example where if
we use geographical or business boundary,

42
00:03:36,742 --> 00:03:43,188
this is likely not to represent the same
functional reality in all scenarios.

43
00:03:43,188 --> 00:03:46,710
You can exclude negligible processes and
for

44
00:03:46,710 --> 00:03:51,714
this you can define a cutoff where
processes can only be excluded

45
00:03:51,714 --> 00:03:57,660
if they contribute to less than this
cutoff percentage to the total impact.

46
00:03:57,660 --> 00:04:02,326
Processes that are identical
in the different scenario can

47
00:04:02,326 --> 00:04:07,179
potentially be excluded, but
only if the intermediary flows

48
00:04:07,179 --> 00:04:11,767
of these processes are strictly
equal between scenario.

49
00:04:11,767 --> 00:04:17,923
So if the quantity use of this process
per functional unit is exactly the same,

50
00:04:17,923 --> 00:04:22,866
and beware, because if the yield,
the outcome is different,

51
00:04:22,866 --> 00:04:29,514
the total output is different, it's likely
that this flow will also be different.

52
00:04:29,514 --> 00:04:35,907
Allocation between co-products,
like between wheat and stroke.

53
00:04:35,907 --> 00:04:40,269
What are the hierarchy recommended by ISO?

54
00:04:40,269 --> 00:04:45,543
First, we try to separate the process and
attribute all or

55
00:04:45,543 --> 00:04:50,505
some of the processes to one co-product or
the other.

56
00:04:50,505 --> 00:04:52,411
Could we separate them?

57
00:04:52,411 --> 00:04:57,459
Second, we want to consider
the possibility to do to

58
00:04:57,459 --> 00:05:02,510
use system expansion where
we will extend the system

59
00:05:02,510 --> 00:05:07,577
boundary to include a proven
substituted product.

60
00:05:07,577 --> 00:05:16,229
And then account for the avoided emission
of this product as a bonus to our impacts.

61
00:05:16,229 --> 00:05:20,862
Third, we can use physical
allocation based on mass or

62
00:05:20,862 --> 00:05:25,811
energy content, but
only if there is a direct causality.

63
00:05:25,811 --> 00:05:33,740
So don't use mass if total impact
are not directly related to mass.

64
00:05:33,740 --> 00:05:37,836
Finally, we can use
financial allocation nearly

65
00:05:37,836 --> 00:05:42,030
in every case as a comparative
allocation method or

66
00:05:42,030 --> 00:05:47,799
as a default allocation method when
we cannot apply the other method.

67
00:05:47,799 --> 00:05:52,173
And again,
we are based on causality as a measure of

68
00:05:52,173 --> 00:05:55,346
the incentive here for production.

69
00:05:55,346 --> 00:06:00,618
On the inventory sides of extraction and
emission of resources and

70
00:06:00,618 --> 00:06:04,958
emission, data consistency and
quality is crucial.

71
00:06:04,958 --> 00:06:09,907
So, beware to take the database
which are consistent,

72
00:06:09,907 --> 00:06:16,122
which are comprehensive,
covering all necessary inventory flows,

73
00:06:16,122 --> 00:06:21,401
and don't mix easily databases
unless you really need to.

74
00:06:21,401 --> 00:06:26,349
And check in that case that for
example electricity mix provide

75
00:06:26,349 --> 00:06:30,281
comparable results in
the different databases.

76
00:06:30,281 --> 00:06:35,027
Otherwise, you might have
real biases in your results.

77
00:06:35,027 --> 00:06:40,266
Third, if we move to the impact
assessment phase of the LCA,

78
00:06:40,266 --> 00:06:47,068
you first select LCA methods that cover
the entire cause effect chain, okay?

79
00:06:47,068 --> 00:06:50,818
And I would recommend in fact
to go presently to damage and

80
00:06:50,818 --> 00:06:53,640
use methods which go to damage by default.

81
00:06:53,640 --> 00:06:58,016
We need to include many information
on fate, transport, dilution,

82
00:06:58,016 --> 00:07:03,144
degradation, and effect like intrinsic
toxicity, soil species sensitivity.

83
00:07:03,144 --> 00:07:09,003
Consider and compare the contribution of
each impact category to total damages.

84
00:07:09,003 --> 00:07:12,605
Don't aggregate everything and
you get a final score, and

85
00:07:12,605 --> 00:07:15,857
you base all your interpretation
on the final score.

86
00:07:15,857 --> 00:07:20,936
Check that the conclusions are robust for
the main impact category

87
00:07:20,936 --> 00:07:26,026
which are contributing to more than
a percent to the total impact.

88
00:07:26,026 --> 00:07:31,261
And use several impact
assessment methods in parallel

89
00:07:31,261 --> 00:07:38,553
to test results robustness like
IMPACT World+ or ReCiPe that we have here.

90
00:07:38,553 --> 00:07:46,083
Finally, for interpretation, compare
results from different angles, okay?

91
00:07:46,083 --> 00:07:51,238
Look at each LCA phase, the inventory
results, the midpoint characterization

92
00:07:51,238 --> 00:07:55,863
results and the damage characterization
of the impact assessment, and

93
00:07:55,863 --> 00:07:59,381
the normalization or
weighting results that we have.

94
00:07:59,381 --> 00:08:03,046
Look at the contribution
of each life cycle stage,

95
00:08:03,046 --> 00:08:07,907
raw material extraction,
product manufacturing, production,

96
00:08:07,907 --> 00:08:12,700
use, waste and disposal, and
of each component of your product.

97
00:08:12,700 --> 00:08:19,169
And especially focus on the one
generating the largest impact or

98
00:08:19,169 --> 00:08:25,056
those where low cost enabled
to have efficient solution.

99
00:08:25,056 --> 00:08:27,706
Consider each substance, okay?

100
00:08:27,706 --> 00:08:33,465
Each elementary flow and
each impact category contribution.

101
00:08:33,465 --> 00:08:38,305
Perform a sensitivity study to
look at the significance and

102
00:08:38,305 --> 00:08:43,437
test the significance of
the differences between scenario and

103
00:08:43,437 --> 00:08:46,941
the robustness of your main conclusions.

